BLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNineteenth-century Europe turned the political status of its Jewish communities into the “Jewish Question,” as both Christianity and rising forms of nationalism viewed Jews as the ultimate other. With the onset of Zionism, this “question” migrated to Palestine and intensified under British colonial rule and in the aftermath of the Holocaust. Zionism’s attempt to solve the “Jewish Question” created what came to be known as the “Arab Question,” which concerned the presence and rights of the Arab population in Palestine. For the most part, however, Jewish settlers denied or dismissed the question they created, to the detriment of both Arabs and Jews in Palestine and elsewhere.This book brings together leading scholars to consider how these two questions are entangled historically and in the present day. It offers critical analyses of Arab engagements with the question of Jewish rights alongside Zionist and non-Zionist Jewish considerations of Palestinian identity and political rights. Together, the essays show that the Arab and Jewish questions, and the Israeli-Palestinian conflict in which they have become subsumed, belong to the same thorny history. Despite their major differences, the historical Jewish and Arab questions are about the political rights of oppressed groups and their inclusion within exclusionary political communities—a question that continues to foment tensions in the Middle East, Europe, and the United States. Shedding new light on the intricate relationships among Orientalism, anti-Semitism, Islamophobia, colonialism, and the impasse in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, this book reveals the inseparability of Arab and Jewish struggles for self-determination and political equality.Contributors include Gil Anidjar, Brian Klug, Amal Ghazal, Ella Shohat, Hakem Al-Rustom, Hillel Cohen, Yuval Evri, Derek Penslar, Jacqueline Rose, Moshe Behar, Maram Masarwi, and the editors, Bashir Bashir and Leila Farsakh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArab-Israeli conflict. 0aJewish-Arab relations. 0aJewsxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aJewsxPolitics and government. 0aNationalismzPalestine. 0aPalestinian ArabsxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aPalestinian ArabsxPolitics and government. 0aPolitical rightszPalestine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  aArab Question.  aIslam.  aIsrael.  aJewish Question.  aJudaism.  aNakba.  aPalestine.1 aAl-Rustom, Hakem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnidjar, Gil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashir, Bashir, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBehar, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvri, Yuval, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarsakh, Leila, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGhazal, Amal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlug, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasarwi, Maram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenslar, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShohat, Ella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z978311